Alexander Acosta, the U.S. Secretary of Labor, reflects on his first day at the department and shares his personal background. He explains that his parents, who fled a dictatorship, were not able to attend college but prioritized entering the workforce to support their family. Acosta, as a first-generation Cuban-American, was able to graduate from college thanks to their sacrifices. He emphasizes the importance of the Department of Labor's mission to foster, promote, and develop the welfare of American workers, job seekers, and retirees. Acosta acknowledges the challenges faced by Americans, such as job loss to overseas outsourcing and the need for skills to fill available jobs. He pledges his fullest effort to fulfill the department's mission and promises to support all Americans in finding good and safe jobs.